                            <h2>VentureCrowd CEO Steve Maarbani spoke to Ticker INVEST about the growing investment in renewable
                                energy.</h2>

                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Watch the recording of the interview below.</strong>
                            </p>
                            <div class="fluid-video-wrapper">
                                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/xWNlaF31G3g" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"></iframe>
                            </div>
                            

                            <div class="post-body-rich-text text-left mt-5">

                                <h2>Short on time? Here's the summary:</h2>
                            </div>
                            <br/>
                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Renewable energy milestone</strong>
                            </p>
                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>
                                    Last year, Australia’s renewable energy industry reached a significant milestone with more than a quarter of the country’s
                                    total electricity generation coming from renewable sources (27.7%).

                                </li>
                                <li> This has more than doubled in the last 5 years. At the same time, the total energy produced
                                    from fossil fuels dropped by 13%.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Looking ahead, a recent report by PwC (called The Future of Energy) forecasts that Australia could be using 80% renewable
                                    energy within 20 years.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Most of Australia’s global trading partners are adopting net-zero emissions by 2050, a number of state governments are doing
                                    the same thing, and a big group of major Australian corporations, including Coles &amp; Woolworths,
                                    are taking the lead and voluntarily committing to those targets.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Based on current data, forecasts, and more and more companies committing to targets, the renewable energy sector has a huge
                                    amount of growth in it.
                                </li>
                            </ul>

                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Improving carbon footprints.</strong>
                            </p>

                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>
                                    All around the world, there are many great examples of companies (in sectors that are traditionally big polluters) taking serious steps to improve their carbon footprint. Such moves are not just on the fringes of the economy any more.

                                </li>
                                 <li> Three examples of companies taking these big steps: <br/>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>1.</b> <a href="https://www.fonterra.com/nz/en.html">Fonterra </a> - the world’s largest dairy producer - is internally working on innovation to reduce &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; methane emissions from its cows. <br/>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>2.</b> In the car industry, <a herf="https://www.tesla.com/en_au">Tesla </a> has obviously been a pioneer for a long time, but this week<a href="https://www.porsche.com/australia/"> Porsche</a>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; announced that its entry-level Taycan 4 Cross Turismo would be an electric vehicle. <br/>
                                    &nbsp;&nbsp; <b>3.</b> In the mining sector <a href="https://www.fmgl.com.au/">Fortescue Metals</a> has partnered with Indonesian coal giant <a href="http://www.adaro.com/">PT Adaro Energy</a> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;to announce that they are working on a project to fast-track the creation of a worldwide green hydrogen industry. <br/>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Improving carbon footprints and moving towards renewable energy to meet emissions targets is no longer a fringe issue. It is very much front and center, it’s at the top of the agendas of the world’s largest corporations, and it’s great to see many of them really rising to the challenge.
                                </li>
                                
                            </ul>

                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Investors’ role in shift towards renewable energy.</strong>
                            </p>
                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>
                                    Investors are driving the transition by companies to a renewable energy future.

                                </li>
                                <li> Global investment from major investors has continued to shift from fossil fuels into renewable energy projects because customers are demanding it. 
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    A good example of that is <a href="https://www.tiltrenewables.com/">Tilt Renewables</a>, an Australian company that owns wind farms in Australia and NZ. 
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    In December last year one of its major shareholders indicated it was considering selling -  which started a bidding war by a number of major investment groups.

                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    One of them was a consortium made up of AGL Energy, Australia's Future Fund and Queensland Investment Corporation, offered $7.80 per share, this month a Canadian pension fund offered $8.00 per share, forcing the consortium to increase its offer to $8.10 per share.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The $8.10 final figure is more than double the share price of the company in December! Interest from investors in a wind farm company resulted in its share price doubling in 4 months.
                                </li>
                            </ul>

                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Everyday investors and the renewable energy sector.</strong>
                            </p>
                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>
                                    The contribution of renewable energy to total electricity generation is now more than 27% - that’s more than doubled in 5 years

                                </li>
                                <li> <a href="https://www.pwc.com.au/">PwC</a> is forecasting; it could contribute up to 80% of total electricity within 20 years.

                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Most of Australia’s global trading partners have committed to net-zero emissions by 2050.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    A number of major companies in very traditional sectors are taking bold steps to reduce their carbon footprint.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Institutional investment into renewable energy projects globally has now exceeded investment into fossil fuels.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The message for investors is that renewable energy is no longer a fringe issue - it is a very important investment story and one that has strong growth in it over the next 5 years.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    At <a href="https://www.venturecrowd.com.au/s/">VentureCrowd </a>we are actively looking to find and fund companies that are innovating in the renewable energy space.                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Investors who are interested in participating should look out for those opportunities and invest early.
                                </li>
                            </ul>

                           
